data.title: Krnnivsa
data.text:
U.S. Consulate conducts workshop for South Indian scriptwriters.

A five-day workshop on screenwriting, jointly organised by the US Consulate General in Chennai and the Global Media Makers (GMM), for ten emerging women scriptwriters from South India, concluded in Alappuzha. 2 students miss Pushpa and Miss meghna from KRNNIVSA also were participated in the workhop

The workshop was led by US and Indian filmmaker mentors, including Ruth Atkinson, Pamela Ribon and GMM Fellow Triparna Banerjee, as part of the ‘screenwriting retreat’ organised for the emerging women scriptwriters from February 10-14, the US Consulate General in Chennai

Popular Indian filmmakers Mahesh Narayanan, Indu Lakshmi, Sudha Padmaja Francis and GMM Fellow Christo Tomy shared valuable insights from their personal experiences

Award-winning film editor Bina Paul, former artistic director of the International Film Festival of Kerala, collaborated with Film Independent to design the workshop and shortlist the participants.

A master class by Shri Reghunath Palery, the well-known Malayalam writer of Novels, Short Stories and Screenplays is being organised at K R Narayanan National Institute of Visual Science & Arts from Monday, 13th November, 2023.

In the starting session of the Masterclass, Shri Reghunath Palery gave detailed insights as to how stories emerge from daily life. He took the students through a personal journey of his own life illustrating how incidents and events from life become inspirational seed ideas for fictional stories. Through engaging interactions, he further plans to deconstruct the process that enables him to create a story. And the process as to how a story becomes a film script. He plans to elaborate upon the methodology of story writing and character design, colouring it with various examples from literary and cinematic work.

The five-day workshop is meant to emphasize on the fundamental process of screenwriting. He will share his thoughts about the history, traditions, trends and philosophies dominant in the screenwriting craft, on how a film emerges from thoughts of a writer. Through the five days he will take the students through the development of idea into a story and its treatment. This will be followed by intensive class on Characterisation and development of setting and arranging part of the elements in the narrative. On the third day the students will be guided on various aspects of screenplay. They will write a scene incorporating all elements. The concluding phase of workshop will dwell on mise-en-scene. The workshop is fully experiential and exercise based.

De construction of Directorial Process:

A Master Class by celebrated Malayalam Film Director Shri Dileesh Pothen was organised on Wednesday, 18th October, 2023 at KRN campus.

In the intensive interactive session given to the students of KRNNIVSA Shri Dileesh Pothen explained his Directorial Process from inspiration to the final screen.

The final session was a script realization session with the direction department students, where he took a script in detail and discussed his approach to direction.

His film JOJI was screened in the evening and a post screening discussion was also held.

Master Class by P F Mathews

A master class by P F Mathews, the well-known Malayalam writer of Novels, Short Stories and Screenplays was organised at K R Narayanan National Institute of Visual Science & Arts on Monday, 16th October, 2023.

In the first session of the Masterclass titled ‘Story Significance” P.F.Mathews, deconstructed the process that enables him to create a story. He enlightened the students’ giving insights to the methodology of story writing and character design, colouring it with various examples from literary and cinematic works.

Emphasizing on the fundamental aspects of screenwriting, he pointed out how majority of the Malayalam screenplays exist as only literary works, without utilising the possibilities of the cinematic medium. He shared his thoughts about the history, traditions, trends and philosophies dominant in the screenwriting craft, on how a film can be political without sacrificing its artistic integrity, also daring to point out the feudalistic and patriarchal biases in much revered Malayalam films like Nirmalyam. (M.T. Vasudevan Nair, 1973). Then he moved on to a detailed analysis of the aesthetic approaches of filmmakers Yasujiro Ozu and Krzysztof Kieslowski.

The afternoon session was a detailed script-to-screen study of select scenes of Kieslowski’s Three Colours Blue (1993). The final session consisted of a personal interaction of the students and teachers of the institute with the guest, where he shared his own experiences in the Malayalam film industry citing clear instances from his work. He maintained how cinema was essentially a director’s craft, where the screenwriter is only a collaborator in shaping the Director’s vision. The Masterclass concluded with the screening of the film Ee.Ma.Yau, written by P.F.Mathews and directed by Lijo Jose Pellissery.
